<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,325,710]" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">
This species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[522,607,325,350]" name="Finland" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Finland</collectingCountry>
and is recorded in Europe and North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Morison" box="[1141,1304,325,350]" pageId="6" pageNumber="411" refString="Morison, G. D. (1957) A review of British glasshouse Thysanoptera. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 109 (16), 467 - 520. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1957. tb 00334. x" type="journal article" year="1957">Morison 1957</bibRefCitation>
), but 
<bibRefCitation author="Bhatti" pageId="6" pageNumber="411" refString="Bhatti, J. S. (1998) The European and North American greenhouse pest Leucothrips nigripennis Reuter, the fern thrips (Terebrantia: Thripidae), lives outdoors in India. Oriental Insects, 32, 153 - 175. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00305316.1998.10433772" type="journal article" year="1998">Bhatti (1998)</bibRefCitation>
recorded it from 
<collectingCountry box="[422,480,361,386]" name="India" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">India</collectingCountry>
with a detailed redescription and account of its habitat. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" box="[1273,1436,361,386]" pageId="6" pageNumber="411" refString="Mound, L. A. (1999) Saltatorial leaf-feeding Thysanoptera (Thripidae, Dendrothripinae) in Australia and New Caledonia, with newly recorded pests of ferns, figs and mulberries. Australian Journal of Entomology, 38, 257 - 273. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1440 - 6055.1999.00112. x" type="journal article" year="1999">Mound (1999)</bibRefCitation>
recorded the species from 
<collectingCountry box="[448,550,397,422]" name="Australia" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Australia</collectingCountry>
with descriptions of male and larva II. It is easily distinguished from the other four species by the white body with dark fore wings. It is recorded as a pest of ferns in greenhouses (
<bibRefCitation author="Morison" pageId="6" pageNumber="411" refString="Morison, G. D. (1957) A review of British glasshouse Thysanoptera. Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 109 (16), 467 - 520. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1957. tb 00334. x" type="journal article" year="1957">Morison 1957</bibRefCitation>
), and has caused problems to cultivated ferns in 
<collectingCountry box="[749,852,469,494]" name="Australia" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Australia</collectingCountry>
but is not usually regarded as a serious pest (
<bibRefCitation author="Mound" pageId="6" pageNumber="411" refString="Mound, L. A. (1999) Saltatorial leaf-feeding Thysanoptera (Thripidae, Dendrothripinae) in Australia and New Caledonia, with newly recorded pests of ferns, figs and mulberries. Australian Journal of Entomology, 38, 257 - 273. https: // doi. org / 10.1046 / j. 1440 - 6055.1999.00112. x" type="journal article" year="1999">Mound 1999</bibRefCitation>
). The male is recorded only from 
<collectingCountry box="[591,697,505,530]" name="Australia" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Australia</collectingCountry>
. This thrips is here newly recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[1158,1225,506,529]" name="Japan" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Japan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="411" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,325,710]" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,541,566]" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Body including legs uniformly white, fore wing dark brown (
<figureCitation box="[1018,1088,541,566]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1763,1786]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,193,1742]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[157,1429,193,1742]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Japanese species of Dendrothripinae. Leucothrips, female 1–3. (1) L. furcatus; (2) L. nigripennis; (3) L. piercei. Pseudodendrothrips, 4–10; (4) P.bhattii, female; (5) P.darci, female; (6) P.lateralis, female; (7) P.lateralis, male:(8) P. maculatus, female; (9) P.maculatus, male; (10) P.mori, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1094940/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
); antennal segments III and IV with forked sensoria (
<figureCitation box="[396,479,577,602]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1720,1743]" captionTargetBox="[193,1390,195,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[187,1400,193,1700]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Leucothrips furcatus, female 11–13. (11) Head &amp; pronotum; (12) Antennal segments III–VII; (13) Abdominal tergite VII.Leucothrips nigripennis, female, 14–16; (14) Head &amp; pronotum; (15) Antenna; (16) Metascutum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1094942/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
); sculpture on pronotum, meso- and metanota with narrow fringe (
<figureCitation box="[1228,1358,577,602]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1720,1743]" captionTargetBox="[193,1390,195,1692]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[187,1400,193,1700]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Leucothrips furcatus, female 11–13. (11) Head &amp; pronotum; (12) Antennal segments III–VII; (13) Abdominal tergite VII.Leucothrips nigripennis, female, 14–16; (14) Head &amp; pronotum; (15) Antenna; (16) Metascutum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1094942/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="411">Figs 14, 16</figureCitation>
). Male very similar to female but sensoria on antennal segments III and IV simple.
</paragraph>
